Butcher's Block
Raffles Arcade L2-02
328 North Bridge Rd
Singapore 188719

Discover some of the worldâ€™s finest cuts of meats personally sourced and procured by Chef RÃ©my Lefebvre from dedicated farms that show utmost care and respect for their livestock at Butcher's Block. These premium meats are cooked using the time-honoured craft of wood fire employing a variety of techniques, such as smoking, grilling and slow cooking in embers, to impart distinct flavours and aromas.

Butcherâ€™s Block is stylishly adorned with cobalt blue hues, complementary dark wood panelling and bold brass furnishing and accents which set the tone for a convivial evening of hedonistic pleasure. The restaurant features a glass cooler aptly named The Vault, displaying fine cuts of meats, next to the Open Kitchen, where guests can watch the chefs preparing and cooking meats to perfection. Adding to the visual appeal is The Library, an exposed wine cellar that houses more than 200 different wine labels, including a good selection of natural wines.

Everyone whoâ€™s tried this set told us the dessert is awesome, and we concurred when we tried it too. At first glance, I thought it similar to the dessert in the first rempah meal, so I thought I knew what to expect. But the coconut purin was like nothing I expected.

Very sweet with an intensity that knocks you off your feet, it then draws you up and in again for another taste. I do try to be prudent with dessert and will usually share half with hubs. But after the first taste, I dug in greedily and gleefully for another spoonful, and another, and another till my tub was totally depleted. What joy!

And only after I was done, I curiously went to research what a purin is. And laughed with recognition, when my online search turned up Pompompurin - a good-natured Golden Retriever character introduced by the Japanese company Sanrio in 1996. Known also as the Pudding Dog, he loves cream caramel puddings, which is what a purin is.

Ah, so that is it - a cream caramel pudding, and @mustardseed_sg gives it an Asian twist - a coconut purin. A lover of coconut and the Hokkaido milk pudding, I understand now why this coconut purin concoction has me so strongly in its spell. What a fitting dreamy finish to a wonderful meal. Happy 1st anniversary again, @mustardseed_sg!

We always enjoy a good ochazuke, where adding the dashi soup or freshly brewed green tea over the rice and desired ingredients means that the rice grains are still distinct and not soggy. This ochazuke from @mustardseed_sg was a really nice surprise, because weâ€™ve yet to try burdock. And at first, I thought it was chicken and onions on top of the rice. The chicken was tasty and nicely grilled, and the long, form strands of burdock added a nice textural contrast to the tender chicken. But the real winner of the fish, I thought, was the broth - very soothing and smooth, it was humming with taste and made the whole dish really come into its own. All of us loved it, especially our youngest boy, who had like 3 bowls!

Kiyoshi is a new Japanese restaurant in Amoy Street that specialises in inaniwa udon, a type of udon made in the Inaniwa area of Inakawa machi, Akita prefecture. This cream coloured udon is hand-stretched and is slightly thinner than regular udon, yet thicker than somen or hiyamugi noodles.
.
The most important part of the making process is the repeated hand-kneading technique which helps it to achieve its thin, smooth and delicate, melt-in-your mouth texture.
.
This dish is called Tem Chirashi Udon ($16.80). Cold Inaniwa udon with assorted tempura: scallop, cherry tomato, mushroom, avocado and capsicum.
.
The cold noodle is lightly seasoned and in each bite you can taste smooth and bounc udon. The crispy assorted tempura compliments the udon perfectly.
.

To say the beef korokke in keema curry is inventive is almost an understatement. This dish from @mustardseed_sgâ€™s izakaya set was a wonderful marriage of great izakaya tradition and spicy Asian fare. Hailing from India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal and Afghanistan, keema curry comprises potato, meat, peas, tomato, and garlic. This traditional spiced curry, combining the flavours of cumin, cassia, cardinal and coriander, is flavourful and aromatic. Usually eaten with rice, wraps or naan, @mustardseed_sg pairs it with the Japanese korokke, or Japanese potato croquettes with a crunchy panko crust. Keeping yo the same meat - beef - gives the overall dish a good consistent theme, allowing the diner to focus on the beautiful combination of different cuisines instead. We warmed up the dish slightly in the oven, freshening the crispy Panko crust, and eaten with the warm keema curry as a dip, this was really a most addictive, moreish izakaya snack!

fullName: Putting The F In Beast âœ¨
description:
For a delectable crustacean filled meal, hit up orchid live seafood - sets are quite value in comparison to dine in + they are very open to customisation (we upsized the weight of our seafood) just drop them a FB msg! 
lobster porridge was the star w sweet, light & subtle yet deep seafood flavours in the translucent broth, a painstaking result of several hours of boiling. The flesh of the shellfish itself was succulent & the rice was nicely al dente, packed separately to ensure the proper temperature (rmb not to include the lobster when reheating so it doesnâ€™t dry out!). Their crab was well-cooked, flesh was fresh + juicyy (quite shiok to tackle this high maintenance dish within the comforts of home) & their unique cream cheese sauce was so yummyy - a sweet savoury mix peppered with the occasional kick from the added chilis, great with deep fried mantous. 
The teochew cold crab: an acquired taste which might be on the drier side for some (mix it in the accompanying vinegar/plum sauces or cream cheese gravy if so) but canâ€™t complain about the double shell & yummy roe!! finally, we enjoyed their steven chicken! Quite ingenious style of cooking & marinating chicken that made it taste like marmite pork ribs but dare I say better???(their kitchen has a no pork/lard policy)

One of the best finds this CB season has to be homegrown @mustardseed_sg. The talented trio behind this local FnB are young, humble people, a trio of skilled chefs passionate about food, cooking and always seeking and experimenting with new flavours.

And this week, in the midst of strange covid times, @mustardseed_sg turns one. I didnâ€™t know you from your very beginning, but Iâ€™m very happy that we got to know you over three of your takeaway meals over the CB period. And all three were meals that sparkled, traditional yet with your own interpretations, known, but yet felt new and refreshing.

This izakaya meal is the last in @mustardseed_sgâ€™s series of takeaways, as they revert to regular service. Goodness knows itâ€™s hard enough to get one of these sets, with only 20 produced a week, and so it will be even harder to get an actual seat at their table. Needless to say, it has been an Honour and privilege to try your food and know your skill through these three kits and enjoy it in at home, with our two young ones, who would certainly not have a chance to try it otherwise. They now know what is rempah because of your meals, and their eyes light up, when they hear the words â€œmustard seedâ€. We wish you all the best, and that you grow from strength to strength. And look forward to the day when we two dine at yours. And hopefully, one day in future, our boys will join us at your establishment, wherever that may be, as adults, and Mustard Seed becomes a name we pass down through our generations.

first meal out in phase two had to be a bowl of noodles. and no better bowl of dry ramen in singapore than the version at @singapore_enishi. thiccc, flat noodles mixed in a spicy gravy, paired with sharp raw onion, crispy shallots, tart pickles, juicy duck chashu, charred pork. paired with a wide variety of condiments - japanese seven spice, numbing pepper, black pepper, orange vinegar and kelp vinegar. 
when i walked into the restaurant on saturday night, i was the only customer and had the shop to myself. please support the shop - i hope it stays around for a long time!
P.S: til the end of the month you can get a bottle of @sapporobeer.jp for a dollar with every bowl of ramen!!
.

description:
A BIG THANKS to Karen and the family over at @goldleafsingapore for sending over this delightful Taiwanese Porridge feast! Perfect comfort food especially during this rainy season â˜” Check out the video and other pics â­ï¸â­ï¸
.
Goldleaf Restaurant has been around for quite a while now (nearly 50 years), specialising in Taiwanese Porridge. Their dishes were created by a team of award-winning chefs from Taiwan to ensure maximum authenticity and the highest quality of taste ğŸ‘ğŸ»
.
We received quite a few of their dishes including:
- Steamed Seabass in Light Sauce
- Steamed Pork Patty with Salted Egg
- Omelette with Chye Por (preserved turnip)
- Braised Chicken and Eggplant with Salted Fish
- Japanese Cold Beancurd with Homemade Sauce
- Stir-fried Spinach
- 4x Sweet Potato Porridge
.
Iâ€™m actually not a fan of porridge generally but having this feast while it was raining heavily outside truly changed my mind! The dishes were very warm and hearty and went very well together with the porridge to fill you up. The fish was fresh and well-seasoned, while the pork patty and omelette brought back childhood memories of hearty home-cooked meals. My personal favourite was the braised chicken, eggplant and salted fish. The combined flavour for this was simply awesome and I actually couldnâ€™t stop eating (yes, no surprise, I know ğŸ˜)! All in all, it was a great meal and aside from tasting delicious, it just provided plenty of comfort to soothe the soul (and tummy of course!) ğŸ˜Š
.
Check out their IG or go toÂ goldleaf.com.sgÂ to have a look at their offerings. You can head over to their restaurant in the East at Katong Square, or order in instead by callingÂ 6346 1088.Â Perfect for a rainy day (or any other day) ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»
.
Thanks again Karen for the wonderful meal and for changing my mind about porridge! ğŸ™ğŸ»

â€œKouâ€ by @sushikou.sg ! This is not to be confused with the Kou at Tras. Sushi Kou, helmed by Chef Sakuta, is the newest Sushi-ya to open in Singapore. The 10-seater restaurant soft launched prior to the COVID/CB saga and officially opened recently. I first found Sushi Kou on IG, ordered its beautiful Chirashi Take Out and was convinced I needed to dine in. Promptly got hold of Sakuta San and reserved dinner when it reopened.
*******
Many have asked me about the experience, 2 words, â€œImmaculateâ€ and â€œQualityâ€. It was for me, a very â€œcleanâ€ form and tribute to natural flavours. Sakuta San was not heavy on sauces and the Shari was subtle to play up the main plot. That was perfect. The selection of fish was top quality and nothing ordinary. Either they were young or they were wild. The flavours and textures were really spot on. I thoroughly enjoyed my visit and I am sure many foodies will as well. [Verdict: Terryfic ğŸ‘ğŸ»] Iâ€™m for one a fan of cold brews. â˜•ï¸ What about you? If you are, be sure to check out Wake The Crewâ€™s single origin cold brew concentrates that will definitely perk up your day - be it you need to go out to work or youâ€™re on WFH.

Each bottle of concentrate ($28) is 473ml (16 fl oz) can make SIX to EIGHT servings of cold brew. As a fan of white cold brew (i.e. with milk), I opted for the single origin Brazil Santos concentrate.

One serving of concentrate should be mixed with two servings of fresh milk (for white) or water (for black). If youâ€™re a health-conscious millennial, you can use oat or soy milk instead.

So whatâ€™s the flavour profile like? Strong notes of nuts and chocolate with a finger of sweetness - exactly what was described on the label. The type of notes that I personally prefer since I like my coffee with milk. What I like most about the concentrate as itâ€™s really thick, creamy and not diluted. It certainly perked up my day and gave me the much needed caffeine boost.

Is there a difference between single origin and blends for cold brew? The key difference is that you can really taste the true flavour of the beans from a particular plantation since itâ€™s not mixed with other beans.

Thank you @wakethecrew for sending this over!

One of the best beef stew Iâ€™ve had in a while! The meat was so tender and the mashed potatoes, super creamy. One of the things I was craving to eat during CB was fish and chips but didnâ€™t wanna order delivery cuz itâ€™d get soggy. So we ordered some here and it was nice and crispy. Thick haddock fish that was perfect on itâ€™s own; no sauce needed. Itâ€™s hard to find scotch eggs in Singapore. When we were up in London, this was something my hubby MUST eat. So weâ€™re really happy to have some here. Lad&Dad used to be at Maxwell hawker centre but have now moved to one of those places under the Tanjong Pagar flats facing Craig Road. This is an even better location with excellent chill out vibes!!! Great food and great atmosphere. Itâ€™s so good, Iâ€™ve already made plans to return with my colleague this week lol...itâ€™s really nice to find a British comfort food hangout place... .

description:
I ordered @wearehopstationsg spiced lamb chops during quarantine, and they delivered alongside my order of two 2.5 litre draught beers. The draught beers were priced at a bargain of $28 considering that itâ€™s 2.5 litres of decent craft beer, while the lamb chops were kind of pricey at $28, all before the $10 delivery charge. â €
â €
The lamb chops were deliciously decent. It was more herb-forward than spice, but it worked well to combat the inherent gaminess of lamb. Thereâ€™s a little pinprick of heat from what I assume is the paprika that was mixed together with the herbs. It was grilled to well done, but was acceptably juicy & tender.â €
â €
The lamb sauce (paging Gordon Ramsay, I repeat, paging Gordon Ramsay) on the side was rich & salty, and was a decent lubricant for the meat. However, the magnificent mint garlic aioli on the side was the lambâ€™s one true soulmate. It was mildly minty, but it was ravishingly refreshing from the heavy, salty flavours of the lamb. Itâ€™s almost like a tzatziki sauce, really.â €
â €
The roasted spuds & vegetables were a perfect accompaniment to the lamb, and were a nice break from the meaty onslaught that is the lamb.â €

I ordered a whole lot of food, including â€œTraditional Claypot Rice with Preserved Meat and Pork Bellyâ€ because I am constantly on a hunt for good cantonese claypot rice, â€œStir Fried Homemade Hor Fun with sliced Kagoshima Wagyuâ€ because it said â€œHome-madeâ€, and â€œClaypot Free Range Chicken with Glutinous Rice Wine, Ginger and Woodearsâ€ because I love Rice Wine. Enjoyed most of the dishes, very cantonese.
*******
I used to visit @majesticrestaurantsg when it was at Bukit Pasoh. Enjoyed the slight fusion and catchy creations by Chef @yongbingngen . I vividly remember Wasabi Prawn was one of his first few creations and that trend caught on like wild fire in Singapore (I may be wrong, it was that long ago). - Cherry tomatoes
- Farfalle
- Pesto sauce
- Chicken broth
- Garlic powder
- Crushed red pepper
- Coarse black pepper
.
*Preparation*
- Cut chicken fillet into thin slices and marinate with oyster sauce, a little sesame oil and ground black pepper.
- Stir fry minced garlic with butter and extra virgin olive oil. I love olive oil so I added more olive oil and also, the pasta won't be too dry.
- Once the minced garlic turns fragrant but not brown, quickly add in thinly sliced chicken fillet and cherry tomatoes and stir fry with the garlic together.
- After that, add in 1 cup of chicken broth and mix well with the ingredients. Pour in the cooked Farfalle into the broth and stir fry.
- Add an adequate amount of pesto sauce, depending on the portion of pasta you cook and mix the pasta and broth evenly.
- Sprinkle a little of crushed red pepper, garlic powder and coarse black pepper into pasta and mix well.
- Dribble some pine nuts on pasta and serve. Enjoy!
.
.

description:
So blessed to be bless by 1A Crispy Puff with this box of 8pcs crispy puff. 
Super love 1A Crispy puffs for their uniquely thin pastry crust that are multilayered and really crispy yet the texture was soft. It's buttery, thin, flaky and light and crumbles easily in your mouth which adds an addictive crunch to it.Â Though deep fried, it wasnâ€™t oily.Â The curry chicken puff filling is more liquid unlike the traditional pasty fillingsÂ and the curry filling is very generous. Oh and one thing I like about 1A is every time I buy puffs from them, they are always nice and warm.Â I think that's really the key in providing consistency in quality and taste. I hope they have more outlets open ğŸ˜

Personally, I feel that the various types of frozen chicken offered by Tay's just has that edge and tastes more like actual chicken. This chicken breast fillet is no different and the quality is clear when you try it. ğŸ‘ŒğŸ» .

Drizzle some mayo (not too much!) and u got yourself a yummy meal. I must say I was quite impressed with the fillet. All I did was throw it into the airfryer for a bit and voila! You can taste the quality in the meat and it was tender. I'm personally not a fan of chicken breast but this was tender and tasty and went well with the TAC combo above. Convenient indeed and decently healthy too. I personally would choose Tay's over most other brands out there and so far, I've never been disappointed. description:
Lollaâ€™s sea urchin pudding - Uni on a squid ink pudding. This is the dish that is synonymous with Lolla - when you think of @lollasg, this is the dish that comes to mind.

For the uninitiated, it is an exotic, unimaginable concoction. And I had no idea what to expect. I only knew that strange as it may sound - a seafood pudding?! - I had to try it, because there are only rave views out there of this iconic @lollasg dish.

And what a remarkable dish it is indeed! Itâ€™s a savoury-seafood sweet starter, to get you all excited about the rest of your @lollasg meal. So darn good it was, this salty and sweet dish, it can have you reaching out for more. Looks small, but itâ€™s super rich. Perfect for three of us, girls.

A popular dish that is well-known in the Southeast Asian region is the Chicken Rendang and I find it amusing when people argue over the origin of the dish to put their national claim over its creation. Food is meant to be shared and adapting cuisines is part of the human experience. Anyway, my interpretation of the dish is much closer to the Singapore version in that I always leave enough curried gravy to glaze the chicken and rice. Of course, you can cook it until all that spice-rich ambrosial sauce is completely absorbed into the meat. Whatever it is, the linchpin of its success is the long and slow cooking process that breaks down the enzymes of the protein making it irresistibly tender. The secret to its exquisite taste, however, lies in the pounded toasted coconut that gives the curry a nutty depth. Naturally, I always pair it with Nasi Lemak Rice.

description:
So happy that we can finally dine out. And we are here, at the restaurant that first inspired me to start this foodie account, to document my covid-eats and to hopefully promote the FnBs during these challenging times.

Symmetry impressed us in our first takeaway order with their delicious, tasty food, their beautiful restaurant interior when we came to pick up, and most of all, cheerful, friendly and genuine communication and service. There were three ladies behind their IG communication, and all three have been lovely and warm. It was then that I thought: This is such a lovely place with such excellent food and such good, decent people. More should know about them, and try their food.

And along the way, we met many other wonderful restaurants and the people behind them. It would be terrible if any of them fell during these difficult times.

@symmetrysg, you were the first FnB I wanted to write about and announce to the world in this account. And you are the first FnB my son chose to visit when Phase 2 started. I was so excited to be sitting there, enjoying your delicious, beautifully presented food finally, and very happy when one of you girls, Nicole, came out to say â€œHiâ€. Itâ€™s like finally meeting a good pen-pal that you have known so far only through letters and text.

And oh, to eat food hot and nicely plated, haha, what a luxury it felt like after CB. Your dishes taste awesome when hot, and I believe, this is exactly what your talented Chef Nick intended. Our compliments to Chef Nick for this yummy, heartwarming meal of shashuka, beef fusilli, and beef burger. We will return for sure, and with our other little son too.

description:
Opening my last pack of kerupuk from Batam! This is a favourite among colleagues because it is so fragrant and addictive plus plus plus its halal!

Who else feels sad when Muslim colleagues reject your offer of snacks when they are not halal? Get this! ğŸ˜œ

I am sensitive to culture and religion, and would generally try to accommodate all if possible. And I love to share what I love. However, due to religion and dietary constraints, it has always been a challenge getting something that everyone can eat and like.

The workload is extremely heavy with multiple deadlines and new responsibilities, and I am not the only one feeling the strain. At times like this, I will make it a point to stock up on munchies to feed the team.

Which is why I treasure this last pack of kerupuk that in a way connects the teams, regardless of race and religion. Ok, its not perfect coz its not vegan.

And @boonsakthefuzzyeater, this is not a sponsored post. Kthxbye.

There is a restaurant in Vancouver, Canada, that my family absolutely loves. During our Christmas holiday there last December, we took our time to binge-visit Dinesty Dumpling House and had our fill of the fares it boasted. One of my beloved dishes on the menu (and there are too many) is its Sesame Seed Cake with Fried Eggs (a.k.a. Clay Oven Roll), a very popular Taiwanese street snack. 
On this note, I recall that Yong He Eating House@Geylang (Singapore) offers this as well but itâ€™s called toasted bun there. And I used to have it with soya bean milk back when I was in the uni. 
Anyway, since I have an insatiable craving for it, I decided to make it. To my surprise, it is very much like a Chinese version of puff pastry, which is to laminate the dough with layers of fats, oil and flour in this case. It is so adaptable that you can eat it with just about everything but I still prefer to have it with fried egg. The bonus of making it myself, however, is that I can lace the fried egg with a fluffy blanket of meat floss for that extra oomph.

description:
so freaking excited to eat @twomenbagelhouse that i accidentally arrived 30 minutes before opening time. couldnâ€™t wait to bring the bagel home to eat so i devoured it by a standing table near the restaurant. 
this is the johnny bravo, a weekend special from the #tanjongpagar outlet. beef patty, curried scrambled eggs, charred onions and chili sauce between two halves of an â€˜all sortsâ€™ bagel studded with seeds and grains.
pairing the curried egg with chili sauce produced a sweet-spicy taste profile reminiscent of japanese curry with the fruity notes of red chili. the combination of ingredients reminded me of a beef murtabak - in the very best way possible. 
the best way to eat this is to dive in with your hands, get the sauce all over your fingers then lick them clean at the end of the meal. so satisfying.
.
.
.

This group buy thing is seriously a double-edged sword.  In a way I am happy able to get something without having to worry about the minimum order quantity but then you also open up the pandora box to more group buy items, some you would never have heard of until someone in the group proposes LOL ğŸ¤ª

And so, I succumbed to temptation and ordered some Kele roll cakes for Auntie J and shunbian (é¡ºä¾¿ or by the way) order for myself LOL (ok, actually it's the other way round ğŸ¤­). Ps. Please put these in freezer. They really taste like ice cream when you do that.

We ordered:

Mao Shan Wang
Ok this one mum loves! She took a bite and said wah this is good! We can really see the durian flesh!  We finished it immediately after collecting it from the group buy host.

Lychee Martini
We freezed this as recommended and took it the next day.  This is my favourite, not too sweet nor artificial. I was surprised to see the lychee fruit that added an interesting texture. Eh, can't really taste the martini.

Avocado Gula Melaka
We also freezed this.  They are really generous with the mashed avocadoes as you can see from the photo.  I find this a bit sweet and I can't really taste the gula melaka from this one.

Ok mum already warned me not to buy anymore. Ok. I try, but but but rem the importance of having desserts? #åƒç”œå“è„¾æ°”å¥½

First up, the Ramen. Listen to me when I say this is goooood! Authentic and delicious Tonkotsu broth with perfectly textured and cooked ramen noodles. As an avid lover of noodles, I was thoroughly in admiration of how good this tasted. So good that I even forgot to put in the Nori when I finished the bowl! Some might shoot me for saying this, but it reminded me of the ramen I had a couple of times at the popular @ichiran_jp in Tokyo and I dare say this was as good, if not better (maybe because I didn't have to queue ğŸ˜‚). If you order this, get the Gyoza. Just do it! Very delicately made, these just went so well with the ramen. The fillings were well marinated and full of flavour and just the perfect accompaniment to the ramen. As for the Don, this was also pretty good to be honest but unless you're a noodle hater somehow (shame on you) then just get the ramen! ğŸ˜‰ It was so good, I definitely need to order it again! ğŸœğŸ˜
.
Check out their IG and click on this link to order: kanadaya.oddle.me/en_SG
.
Let me know what you think and if you know any other delicious ramen places to try out! ğŸ˜Š

From start to finish, my experience with Tablescape for the order of hubsâ€™s Fatherâ€™s Day meal was effortless, professional and enjoyable. I was miffed when I lost out on their Motherâ€™s Day Special earlier in the year, so made sure I book the Fatherâ€™s Day set way ahead in advance. And really glad I did, because on hindsight or shall I say, â€œhind-tasteâ€ now, it was one exquisite meal, with a nice variety of choice, premium ingredients, cooked excellently and presented to great effect.

There was lobster, veal, parmesan flan, foie gras, lagsagne, seabass, wagyu beef cheeks, and a beautiful signature bread platter with amazingly soft, fragrant butter. Possibly even better than the Motherâ€™s Day set I missed!

It was nice to know that a few of the courses were borne of Chefâ€™s own childhood experiences and special memories, including that very light and tasty traditional beef lagsagne, that his mum would personally make for his dad every Fatherâ€™s Day. There is nothing like tasting great food and having a glimpse of the personal stories behind them.

Hubs really enjoyed this meal, praising the lovely spread and the finely executed dishes. The boys ate very well, my oldest, claiming itâ€™s the best lunch heâ€™s ever had and telling us he wants to have this again tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow etc. Now, we are keen to dine in one day @tablescapesg and try their other dishes, as well as nice afternoon tea set. Thank you, @tablescapesg, for this wonderful meal to mark this special day. And thank you, @where.is.karl, for this fabulous recommendation - you are spot-on, as always!

I cooked this crab, prawn and lala meal for the family today. Managed to get a great deal for the crab â€“ 3kg for only $60! There was sooo much that I ended up cooking the crabs 3 ways: Chilli, black pepper, and salted egg. I also cooked some laksa prawns that was superbly lemak! Princess loves lala so I made some garlic butter lala from scratch for her. I used the chilli crab and black pepper premix from @primataste for the crabs, and their laksa paste for the prawns. For the salted egg crabs, my own recipe from scratch ğŸ˜‹ It was finger licking good!!! Happy Fatherâ€™s Day to all the Daddies out there and sending a special â¤ï¸ to my own Dad up there. Miss you soooo much. .

With Phase 2, it is possible to dine out again.  You can consider checking out @marusaya_singapore Dashi Shabu Set. Here we sampled the A4 Wagyu Dashi Shabu (S$68 per pax) and Pork Dashi (S$48 per pax).
.
[Slide Left] The vegetable base of the shabu are Chinese cabbage, carrot, kale, tang oh, leak, shimeji, shiitake and myoga / Japanese ginger. Not forgetting the silken tofu as well.Â Then the dashi soup is poured into the pot and heated up. We were told that it is best to lower the fire to simmer after the dashi reaches the boiling point. This will prevent the stock from turning bitter.
.
For the sauce, you can choose between Japanese sesame sauce or Japanese Ponzu sauce. Additional dipping ingredients include chopped spring onions, grated spicy daikon and yuzu paste.
.
[Slide Left x2] We started with A4 Wagyu that comes with dense marbling. We cooked it till medium and it just melts in our mouth. Moo Moo!! The A4 wagyu is already so good, I canâ€™t imagine the A5 Wagyu.
.
[Slide Left x2] Unlike the beef, the pork meat does not have marbling. Instead, the thick layer of fats at the top is equivalent to the marbling in the beef. We cooked it a tad longer than the beef, it produced juicy and succulent pork meat, with a slight chewiness in it. Yummy.
.
For the staple, check out the next post. .
Full review of Dashi Master Marusaya is up on Chubbybotakkoala.com or copy this link https://bit.ly/cbk-575 .
.
.

Beauty in the Pot 
Phase 2 of Singapore's circuit breaker restrictions have been lifted, and this means being able to dine inside restaurants again!

Headed to Beauty in the Pot over the weekend, and it is a capable alternative to the ever-popular Hai Di Lao. We got the twin pot shabu with the flavours: beauty collagen and spicy. Really love the pork, that has a melt-in-your-mouth texture. The vegetables were very fresh, and service was great too. They gave more bottles of collagen broth for refills - you will definitely get your fill of nutrition from this meal. 
I recommend that you try this, instead of straightaway going for Hai Di Lao. You just might find this better.

description:
Our first bake sale is here, and it's a fundraiser!

Recently, there has been a lot of negative news surfacing on social media, and one of it is the Yemen crisis.

Yemen, a country in the Middle East, is on the verge of extinction. Yemen is experiencing a civil war, a famine and a pandemic amongst other things. We have created some informative posts that explain more about what Yemen is facing right now.

Yemen needs our help, which is why we have decided to raise funds for the Yemen crisis through this bake sale. 50% of profits generated from this sale will be donated to Islamic Relief. If you would like to make additional monetary donations, you can do so through the link in our bio as well! We will post proof of donations on our highlights once we have collated the final amount.

Apart from our date cinnamon bites, we have decided to expand our menu to sell brownies as well! This is a one-time menu made for the fundraiser, and there are limited slots, so its fastest fingers first! Swipe to the end or watch our story highlights to view the price list.

Your donations will go towards providing food, clean water and healthcare needs to more than 2.5 million people. Every little bit counts!

Click on the link in our bio to order!
Pre-orders close on 24 June 2020, 8pm.

Delivery: 27 june 2020, after 5pm
Delivery fee: $8
Self-collection: 27 June 2020, 5.30pm - 6pm @ Woodlands MRT

description:
A BIG THANKS to Jacqueline and the terrific team at Sinn Ji Hainanese Chicken Rice for sending over this fabulous feast! ğŸ˜
.
Being a chicken rice lover, I was excited to sample their Hainaese Chicken Rice. When it arrived, I was pleasantly shocked at the feast that they generously sent over! This included both poached and roasted chicken, stir fried bak choy vegetables (nai bai), 5-spiced chicken roll, and a huge serving of their curry fish! ğŸ˜± Also included was a whole array of their condiments to ensure the meal was properly savoured. And savour we did! ğŸ˜‰
.
First, the chicken rice. It was really good! The rice was not oily yet really fragrant (good enough for you to want second helpings!). The chicken was cooked well and I preferred the poached version with ginger and chili sauces on the side. The veggies looked so normal but they were just so good! Cooked HK style, they were silky smooth and full of flavour (not sure what special sauces they used!). Too good! The chicken roll (ngoh hiang) was also really good with perfect texture and very yummy chunky meat inside. Now the curry.. DAMNNNN this was good! ğŸ¤¯ The fish (snapper) was very fresh and cooked perfectly well (not overcooked) and the curry was just awesome! Very thick, spiced flavourfully and creamy, this just brought so much comfort and joy with every spoonful. I also absolutely loved the chunky tofu puffs that came with it. Simply bliss! ğŸ¥°
.
I highly recommend this and you can check them out at @sinnjithomsonroad or drop by to have a feast at their Thomson Road outlet. If you rather stay home like me, you can order by calling them at 6258 0855 (or Whatsapp 9096 0974) ğŸ‘ŒğŸ» .
.
.
.
.
.
.

ATIPICO Kit - â€œPoliedric Balance of Creative, Refreshing, Traditional, Addictive, Healthy & Guilty Dishes. Those who know, knowâ€. @atipicohomechef .
*******
Kit 7 - French Mediterranean Menu . Comes with Signature Sourdough, Olives Tapenade, Mediterranean No-sheâ€™ll Quiche, â€œGigot de 7 Heuresâ€, Confit Root Vegetables and a â€œTarte Au Citron Meringueeâ€. The foodie bud @alleatsbigandsmall has been following the kits and raves about ATIPICO. I was elated when she sent a set over. I must say the food was quite artisanal, Nordic with some beautiful touches. The way I saw it, the main plot evolved round the Sourdough (which was an absolute stunner, probably the best Iâ€™ve had), the dishes were the supporting cast and you decide what the various sub-plots should be. Whether you have the Sourdough with a spread of the Tapenade, or have it with the gorgeous velvety delicious 7-hr Roast Lamb gravy and even just on its own with good french butter. It was a delicious meal, flavours were popping all over and you canâ€™t stop with that Sourdough. The Lemon Meringue was no less. Lovely zest to finish the meal, I enjoyed how it cut through, it did not feel heavy and I was reaching for more. ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚

Where did you go for your first meal out in Phase 2? I went to check out Chef Chik (01-36) at Haig Road Market & Food Centre - a stall that I wanted to try for quite some time. Think restaurant quality food at hawker prices. Youâ€™ll be rewarded with yummy steamed Cantonese dishes and double boiled soups.
â€¢
[Verdict: Terryfic ğŸ‘ğŸ»] Steamed Threadfin Belly (Market Price; Pic 1). I really enjoyed this dish. The fish was really fresh and the flesh was so soft that it just melts in your mouth. I like the garlic soy sauce seasoning thatâ€™s prepared by the chef-owner himself although its on the saltier side. Lots of spring onions, coriander and some chilli padi for garnish. It boosted the flavour of this dish.
â€¢
[Verdict: Terryfic ğŸ‘ğŸ»] Black Fungus Steamed Chicken ($8; Pic 2). A classic Cantonese dish that was well-executed. The chicken was really fragrant, smooth and tender. And I like the slight crunch of the black fungus. The homemade sauce was really delicious too. Those who donâ€™t like bones in their chicken may not enjoy this so much.
â€¢
[Verdict: InTerrysting ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»] Oyster Sauce Kai Lan ($3/6; Pic 4). Some greens are good for you so we ordered this. The kai lan was blanched properly and the stem was crunchy. Itâ€™s good for what it is.
â€¢
Iâ€™ll be back to try the steamed fish head (popular with regulars) and double boiled soup.

description:
Fatherâ€™s Day dinner for my FIL. We love soup a lot (typical Cantonese family lol) so steamboat is something we love too. Weâ€™re still not ready to dine out so getting a prepacked ready to eat set like this makes it super easy for busy people like me. Hotpot Master is under the Neo Group so without a doubt, the quality was great. We had the collagen soup and even right at the start, it already tasted so yummy. Totally explains why itâ€™s their most popular soup. By the end of the meal, the soup had absorbed even more sweetness from the crab, prawns, scallop, etc. It was souperb! ğŸ˜‹ Having steamboat as a family is a wonderful get together and really brings the family closer. We got the set for 2-3 pax and got the additional meats from @donkisg. I got a really good deal with the crab (will share more in another post). But just the set only was sooooo much food! The team at @hotpot_master_delivery was really friendly and even threw in a complimentary tobiko prawn paste. So happy they did cuz I managed to try it and itâ€™s so soft! ğŸ¤¤ MUST ORDER!!! Overall this was a fantastic meal. They even packed in disposable plastic table cloth, tissue box, cutlery, etc. Everything was packed clean and came in individual pretty packaging. Oh and their chili, is damn awesome lar! Super spicy and has a lovely sour tang from the lime. That chili sauce was what made the meal mind blowing. No wait, it was the soup. No the tobiko prawns. No..oh gosh I canâ€™t decide. Everything was so good!!! Gonna order from them again next round. No way Iâ€™m gonna set up a steamboat session from scratch again when thereâ€™s an affordable and convenient option for me ğŸ˜ƒ .
.

description:
Iâ€™ve always liked @swissbakesg for their savoury sustenances, but Iâ€™ve never really tried their sweet treats until I was trying to pad out a @grabfoodsg order to meet the minimum delivery. Iâ€™m real glad for that, otherwise I wouldnâ€™t have gotten to relish their pleasant Paradiso Di Nocciola signature cake ($6.90).â €
â €
Itâ€™s taken a different form from its usual size, and it has been shrunken down to this delightful dome. The glistening glaze is 60% dark chocolate, which envelops the alternating layers of vanilla sponge, chocolate sponge and crunchy wafer. Itâ€™s a charmingly chocolatey cake that isnâ€™t saccharine sweet. Instead, the sugar levels are perfectly balanced, as all things should be.â €
â €
The moderate bittersweetness of the dark chocolate exterior helps to average out the sweetness of the moist sponge cake. Itâ€™ll definitely go above & beyond in satisfying the chocolate cravings of any chocaholics without sending their glucose levels skyrocketing. At $6.90, this cake is one of the best out there.â €

This was a huge experience for me â€œMumbai Tapasâ€! Compliments of @sameer.sain (his name has popped up so many times right?). Iâ€™ve been to India a couple of times, mostly south, Kochi, Visakhapatnam. Food in the south, largely curries - diluted, lots of seafood, the kind we are more familiar with in Singapore. North Indian Food seems like a mystery, what the rich and Maharajahs might eat, I never thought much of it until now. Sameer got me the likes of Ragda Pattice, Pav Bhaji, the ultimate Bombay snack - Bhelpuri, a Mumbai legend - Sev Puri; very distinct flavours, complex to some extend. The Pani Puri was fun, like a DIY Kueh Pie Tee, you punch a hole and fill the puffed cracker with a potato mix, sweet Chutney and Tamarind sauce, then pop it in your mouth - one bite insisted Sameer. Hey, not bad, very tasty and profound, I reached out for the next. The Mango Lassi.... canâ€™t remember if I ever had one so delish, not sure why I always had this mental model that a Lassi is diluted like a packet drink, this serving changed everything. What a fantastic meal/ spread of Tapas, some much to learn about food. I was googling and reading about the history of each snack as I ate them, so educational. This was really another feather in the culinary cap. Thank you for sharing the culture and cuisine, Sameer. Love it! #noneedmeepok #fightcovid19 â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”

description:
Spot Prawns and Amaranth Udon
[Ingredients]
/Marinate Prawns/
-12 wild-caught alaskan spot prawns
-1 tsp white wine
-1 tsp salt
-A dash ground white pepper
.
-200g brown rice udon
-2 cups passata/tomato paste
-150g amaranth greens (chopped)
-1 tbsp butter
-3 cloves garlic (minced)
-1 yellow onion (chopped)
-1 tsp smoked paprika powder
-1 tsp cayenne -1/2 cup fresh basil
-A few sprigs of fresh thyme
-1 tsp salt
-1 tsp sugar (optional)
[Steps]
-Cook udon 1 minute less than the total cook time suggested on the package instructions. Rinse cooked udon under cold water, drain, and set aside
-Wash prawns, marinate with wine, pepper, and salt
-Put a pot on low-medium heat. Add butter, minced garlic, and chopped onion. Stir-fry until onion becomes transparent -Stir in spot prawns, amaranth, cayenne, paprika, basil, and thyme. Give it a quick toss -Add tomato paste, salt, and sugar. Let it comes to a boil and simmer for 2 mins
-Add udon and mix well. Turn off the heat and serve
.
.
.

description: I donâ€™t consider myself a huge fan of Korean food, but I quite like this place. The food here is generally of good quality and I very much prefer this over places which prioritise quantity over quality (yes Iâ€™m not a fan of Korean BBQ buffet restaurants haha). We ordered the Pork BBQ Set (Pork Belly and Pork Collar) ($49) and the Seafood Pancake ($16 for medium portion) and it was already quite a substantial spread for 2. Originally wanted to order the Yuzu Soju Cocktail that we like, but unfortunately it wasnâ€™t available, so we just had a bottle of our usual Green Grape Soju ($17) instead. Food was generally not bad, but I think the pork could have been cooked for a shorter time as it became a little tough with our cooking time. The Seafood Pancake was pretty good and it remained crispy for rather long after it was served. description:
A BIG THANKS to Leisha and the fabulous team over at @huaykwangthai for sending over this delicious feast! ğŸ”¥
.
Specialising in Thai Mookata, their business concept is to offer premium meats served up Thai Mookata style. Besides traditional Mookata, they also offer flat-pan soupless Mookata which is similar to a BBQ. Rather unique as there are hardly any other similar places in Singapore for this (if any). To keep their food authentic and maintain their high quality, all their chili sauces and dips are made in house with fresh ingredients imported directly from Thailand.
.
Our feast consisted of quite a few yummy meats as part of their Steak Set â€“ Beef supersteak, pork belly and Thai herb chicken served with veggies and their signature garlic rice. The beef was cooked just right and very tender and flavourful. Best of all, the meats were all paired very nicely with the aromatically spicy green chilli sauce. This sauce is really awesome and definitely my favourite! I also loved the flavour of their garlic rice, which is reminiscent of traditional chicken rice style oily rice (so good with the meats!). The smoky grilled meats really tempt you to head out for a Mookata style experience!
.
Their Mango Salad was the perfect starter to get your appetite fired up. Aside from the meats, their Green Curry Chicken was well made and very fragrant being extremely creamy and thick, just the way I like it. The Thai style fried chicken wings were also delicious (especially when dipped in the magical Green Chilli Sauce!). All in all a great meal indeed!
.
Check them out on their IG or atÂ huaykwangthai.comÂ and now from Phase II onwards, you can drop by at 13 North Canal Road to try them out for yourself! If you would rather stay home like me, you can reach them atÂ 8686 9990Â to place your delivery orders.
.

description:
Have a great phase 2 weekend everyone! Best enjoyed with a slice of bakkwa chiffon cake ğŸ¥³

#foodyocafe

Posted @withregram â€¢ @libbyatsg Cir Breaker Day 52 Tea Break.

We are having the bak kwa chiffon cake from @foodyo_cafe for tea break. The cake uses 100% natural ingredients with no preservatives or chemicals. It's soft and fluffy despite of that, and the lovely bak kwa smell is evident right away when we opened the box. The taste is really nice, a good balance of light sweetness from the cake and fragrant saltiness from the bak kwa bits. 
I'm really quite impressed by it, and at $12 for an 8 inch cake, it is very reasonably priced. I would love to try the other 3 flavours, which are pandan, gula melaka and sweet potato.

You can order the cakes from www.chophupchong.com.sg along with a whole other range of food products from their sister brand Chop Hup Chong. Just buy up to $50, and delivery is free! .

description:
One of my favourite Chinese #desserts has to be Tau Suan, a sweet gelatinous Mung Bean soup. Every time I fried a batch of #youtiao, #tausuan will immediately pop into my mind. Simply put, the fried breadstick is its soulmate and completes the #dessert. Imagine delicious morsels of the salty #cruller soaking up the sweet viscous liquid and forming into luscious balls of sweet-salty goodness. Yup, the beauty lies in the contrasting flavours and texture.

description:
Watched a Netflix feature on Christina Tosi and was so inspired by her. Her school of thought: Donâ€™t be obsessed over frosting the perfect cake. Time spent on the turntable should be better spent elsewhere like on the fillings. We are not in pottery class! Well said indeed!

Hence this weekâ€™s bake: Burnt miso pound cake, a recipe by @christinatosi And I chose to pair it with homemade yuzu curd.
Miso in a dessert? Such unlikely flavors but was pleasantly surprised by the combination of sweet, buttery, savoury.

100g miso
145g buttermilk
100g oil
150g unsalted butter, melted
5 large eggs
300g sugar
290g cake flour
65g brown sugar
11/4 tsp baking powder
1/4 tsp salt

Spread miso out on a baking paper, about 1/4 inch thick
Bake in oven at 205c for 10-15min until miso is brown and burnt at the edges
Let cool slightly 
Grease and flour loaf tin (Iâ€™m using a 8x4.5 inch bread tin)
Blend miso, buttermilk and oil in blender till smooth
Whisk butter and eggs together with the miso mixture
In a separate bowl, whisk all the dry ingredients together 
Pour dry ingredients into the wet ingredients, stir to combine
Bake at 175c for 80min
Let cool for 45min before removing from tin

Yuzu curd recipe: refer to previous post

description:
Our fourth kit with @atipicohomechef, our used-to-be-secret-but-not-very-secret-anymore private chef. This is probably the biggest gem weâ€™ve found in our CB eats - all hits and no misses so far.

The sourdough remains the best and unrivalled weâ€™ve tried, the accompanying pesto/tapenade for the bread always perfect, the vegetable sides delish even to the kids, the main courses always scrumptious and satisfying. And dessert, oh dessert - always dreamily beyond-imagination divine.

The line-up yesterday comprised our favourite @atipicohomechef signature sourdough, an intense olive tapenade with all the beauty of Provence, a masterful Mediterranean no-shell quiche, a melt-in-the-mouth New Zealand lamb, beautifully sweet confit root vegetables, and a tour de force tarte au citron meringueÌe. A perfect meal, which in my opinion, cannot be bettered, except by some excellent wine or bubbly, which we had, of course ğŸ˜„ (Idea for a curated wine add-on to your menu, @atipicohomechef? â—¡Ìˆ) Iâ€™m always excited when Friday approaches. And marvellously, so are the kids! Yesterdayâ€™s meal was hearty and delicious.

Again, I canâ€™t thank my dear friends @annanishaburi and @_ale_duri_ enough for introducing @atipicohomechef to us. So, in turn, we pass on the love to our dear fren @uncle_lim_chiak, who has been sending continuous love to us with the most delectable eats, hidden gems without his direction. And happily, his family loves the food too.

@atipicohomechef, you are pure magic. Thank you, for starting Fatherâ€™s Day weekend, for us with a bang.

Those who know, know.

Probably the last menu and taste of @mustardseed_sg at home, now we join the long wait for the much sought after dine in experience. This CB gave many the unique opportunity to savour the creations and appreciate the talents of young @mkthehansum , @xshinyinx and @jujugohan . Undoubtedly, some of the best Take Outs for me. It did not start that way for me though, to be honest, but as the menu evolved, grew from strength to strength, so did my orientation.
*******
From Rempah to Eurasian, in the past weeks, to the last â€œIzakayaâ€; one recurring theme popped, â€œ.... Reach out with the Soul....â€. Some saw the menu as food, I saw passion and dedication, I saw faith. While many establishments have turned to transactions, whether for survival or impressions, this trio kept to basics - leveraged their strengths and beliefs. Their principled and endearing approach puts me to shame sometimes.
******
Everything on this menu was 11/10. You can feature Rempah influences in Japanese plays after all. This Teochew Uncle predictably enjoyed the Otah Grilled Snapper, but the playful â€œEbi-Heibi Hiamâ€ Burger, the fragrant â€œBeef Korokke with Keema Curryâ€, the fragrant â€œChicken with Burdock Rice, Ochazukeâ€, the surprisingly delicious â€œPork Neck Saladâ€ shouldnâ€™t be second fiddles. How did you guys come up with such a menu anyway??
*******
I am like a kid feeling sad as â€œThe Muppet Showâ€ aired their last episode but thank you for some important lessons and filling the tummy along the way. One of the pluses of the epidemic is that you can get food from popular places like @burntends_sg without having to make reservation months in advance. Every mouth of the slightly burnt leeks, hazelnut and brown butter is a pleasure. The delectable combination of pulled pork, cole slaw, chipotle sauce, brioche bun makes their Sanger a winner and popular choice with diners. For dessert lovers, I highly recommend the Berry Tart with Vanilla Chantilly Cream which is sublime. I understand now the reason for the long waiting list to get into this modern barbecue restaurant.

Have a nice weekend!

YAY my favorite burger place is back and tastes even better than before! Oh how I miss biting into a burger & have the juices squirt out, dripping down my chin (or wassit me salivating? lol) This time round, itâ€™s even better cuz the meat was nice and pink in the centre! ğŸ¤¤ My mum took some of the tempura fries that came with the burger and commented how she loves the crispiness. This is new on the menu and gotta admit how the texture elevates the whole flavour profile when eaten together with the burger. You get a mouthful of soft bun, juicy beef patty, chunky mushrooms, and then that crunchy crispy fries, to end it on a high note. Totally divine ğŸ˜‹ I also bought some deng deng (aka halal bak kwa but beef version) I tossed it into the toaster for that lovely burnt hue but alamak, got too excited eating it that I forgot to take a pic ğŸ˜‚ Incredibly happy that they have opened at the chic chill out happening Bedok Marketplace. Even though they were packed, service was quick and the staff were extremely friendly as always. I guess thatâ€™s what keeps us going back yeah? Not just the great food, but wonderful staff who make you feel like youâ€™re friends :) Oh oh! I also managed to get some free wings during this opening period. Just a warning. If youâ€™re on a diet, donâ€™t order it. I thought I was only gonna have 1 piece but awww man...I ended up having 3! ğŸ˜It was so flavorful and brought back memories of my younger days when my friends and I used to bbq at East Coast. The chicken has this deep smokey smell that reminds me of the food that you get straight from the bbq grill. Very nostalgic and the meat manages to retain the smell, layered in between each bite. The vibes at Bedok Marketplace and the food from The Social Outcast make an excellent choice for a reunion with friends. So happy they moved closer to me! â¤ï¸ . .

description:
Nasi Liwet - rice cooked in coconut milk, chicken broth, salam leaves, lemon grass, to give the rice a rich, aromatic, succulent taste. Our first time trying it. Was quite a heady experience. The opor ayam - a delicate chicken thigh dish cooked in coconut milk scented with galangal and lemongrass - was very tender and fall-off-the-bone. And especially yummy with the dark sweet sauce splashed over it and dipped in the sambal chilli. But I really appreciate the tempeh. Cut in little slivers, every bite was a tasty little l, almost crunchy morsel. Went so well with the chicken. So nice to find a gem like this in authentic home cooking. Get in touch with Christina from @hunterskitchensg, if you fancy some Nasi Liwet goodness.

description:
In the olden days, "Tingkat" or tiffin lunches are common sight, where "char bor kans", "orang gaji" or maids/helpers would bring freshly made lunches to Sir's offices, and return 2 hours later to collect the empty containers home. At times, they were brought to street side hawkers when ordering takeaways. Different foods were placed in the containers, all stacked up one on top of the other hence, the name #tingkat. One layer could be fried rice, another would be fried noodles or different dishes like meats, veggies and soups to go along with rice.
. 
I had the pleasure of having a tingkat lunch from @truebluecuisine by baba @benjaminseck, where different menus were stacked on different layers which was meant for 2. 1st layer was a "bukak napsu" dish or appetizer, Bakwan Kepiting soup. The 2nd layer was rice, with "laok tok" such as beef rendang, chap chye and ngoh hiang, and the 3rd layer was rice with ayam Buah keluak, chap chye and ngoh hiang. Truly, a nod to our heritage.

Perhaps we can start bringing our own tingkat when ordering takeaways to reduce plastic usage, just like the olden days. .

description:
I have a fairy godbrother. And his name is @uncle_lim_chiak. He loves to lim and chiak. Thatâ€™s why, this CB, I also lim and chiak a lot, cos my good brother keeps sending yummy goodies our way. And Iâ€™m not complaining, because Iâ€™ve discovered lots of amazing hidden eats these two months, including some awesome, authentic good home chefs.

Today, my good brother sent us a wonderful meal of Nasi Liwet and Soto Tangkar from the skilled Chef Christina Hunter, of @hunterskitchensg. Nothing fancy, but such comfort food, because of the heart and understanding of heritage and flavours that go into the cuisine. Rich and robust flavours, intensely packed into each dish. Brought out even more, when you add the sauces, which Christina has packed so thoughtfully in separate sachets.

The Nasi Liwet chicken was very tender, moist and yummy, esp when you drizzle the dark sweet sauce over. If you like chilli like me, the level of spice in the sambal prawn with petai beans, was just right - not too spicy to drown out flavours, but spicy enough to whip up a good appetite. And we love that accompanying sambal chilli. Really brought the dish up another notch.

The Soto Tangkar was a rich beef soup. My boy loved the potatoes inside, which were soft and soaked up all the lovely flavours. We love the egg and the meat - very tender and melt-in-your-mouth. We did find it a bit oily though, but just drained off the layer and it was perfect.

Lovely meal, @hunterskitchensg! Thank you, Brother @uncle_lim_chiak, for the treat! You always magick yummy meals our way. Great meal to celebrate the start of Phase 2!

description:
Cheater yuzu curd
Since fresh yuzu isnâ€™t readily available where I am...
Spun off this yuzu curd using the Korean yuzu tea marmalade thatâ€™s easily available in our supermarket. But hey, it does taste very much like your yuzu-al yuzu ğŸ˜†

4 tbsp yuzu tea marmalade 
3 tbsp lemon juice
Zest of 1 lemon
40g sugar
3 large yolks
2 large eggs
50g butter

Mix lemon zest and sugar, rub zest into into sugar and set aside to infuse for 15min
Using double boiler method, with simmering water, whisk eggs and sugar till sugar dissolved
Add yuzu marmalade and lemon juice
Continue whisking constantly till thickened and stir till your desired consistency
Add butter and stir till fully melted
Remove from heat
Strain curd through a sieve for a smoother consistency if you like. But I didnâ€™t because I wanted to keep the yuzu zest in.

This Honeycomb Cake or Bika Ambon (as it is locally known, originating from Indonesia) is simply delicious. Homemade with plenty of passion and heart, no preservatives or artificial ingredients or flavourings are used. Only the freshest high quality ingredients and it also has less sugar, being a healthier alternative to the generic ones out there. You can taste the natural flavours with each bite as they subtly tempt you to take yet another bite.. and another.. and another! ğŸ˜³ The best part is the light chewy texture and it is not too heavy. Many of these harden up in the refrigerator after a few days but this remained absolutely fabulous once popped into the microwave for a few seconds. ğŸ˜
.
I highly recommend to have this with some milk coffee or tea. Personally? Whip up an Earl Grey milk tea with honey and it goes really well with each bite of the cake ğŸ˜‰ğŸ‘ğŸ»

description:
One of the great things about CB is the increased social media presence of more and more fnbs. I know itâ€™s a steep learning curve for many, but itâ€™s really make it so easy for the customer to look for good eats recommendations and sniff out great deals. And that was really how I found @gorojapcuisine.

I followed up on that lead and we enjoyed our first meal in early May tremendously. Looking to try more of their dishes, we ordered again. And their food remains fresh and yummy.

The new items we tried were the crab tempura, the sakana zosui and the yakitori this time.

The crab tempura was really lovely. Good meaty crabs covered in a light, crispy batter. Dunked in the tempura sauce, which was tasty and not too salty, the crab was delicious. The boys loved the yakitori, and we barely had a go at it. The sakana zosui came full of salmon and mushrooms - chock full of ingredients in good old @gorojapcuisine style. Our old favourites of California roll, Chirashi Don and beef steak set remain awesome, as we first remembered it. Love that @gorojapcuisine ensures that our dining experience is not compromised by delivering all its food in thermal bags, in fact, two thermal bags for us - hot items in one, sashimi items in another, to keep all the food fresh and at the right temperature.

If you are thinking of Japanese for your next meal, give @gorojapcuisine a go. @gorojapcuisine has an extensive menu, and fun fact to know: Chef Goro, who trained under Japanese celebrity chef, Iron Chef Koumei Nakamura, has 38 years of experience crafting Japanese cuisine. First-time customers, who use my code - Kelly0724 - will get S$5 off your total bill. This offer is good for the rest of this year 2020. The 1-for-1 sashimi promotion is not to missed. Total bill of non-promo items exceeding S$50.00 gets free delivery. Orders can be placed through whatsapp to 91820553.

description:
World Gin Day may be over (it was last Saturday ICYW), but weâ€™re still in high party spirits toasting with non-alcoholic brand Lyre's Spirit Co, which has launched their Dry London â€˜ginâ€™ in Singapore. Unlike many other de-alcoholised spirits, the Dry London still has a familiar buzz and tastes exactly like its boozy counterpart in terms of bouquet, flavours and mouth-feel. Blended into cocktails, itâ€™s a great way to drink without getting drunk. 
Not convinced? Pick up a bottle on Amazon.sg at $52 or at select Cold Storage outlets and all Marketplace supermarkets. While youâ€™re at it, try out some of their classic cocktail recipes, like this delightfully fruity and Instagrammable Clover Club.

description:
This CB has reinforced the fact that Singaporeans are inseparable from food. We need a morale booster, a required distraction, a comfort, as we combat a common enemy by feeding at home. While Take Outs are readily available, the real Gems are those from the home kitchens. And when we think about home kitchens, one persona (Ibu, Gadis, foodie) comes to mind..... @singaporeliciouz !! Super generous and like I said the last time, if she msgs you, you better respond. Else you can kiss the goodie goodbye.
*******
This time she made Lemper and the much talked about Goma Cheesecake! If you had her Nasi Arem, this Lemper was just as unforgettable. Luxurious savoury snack filled with Pedas Ikan Bilis, I risked Gout to eat these puppies and 4 werenâ€™t enough. I will trade Chang for these anytime.
Ok, that Goma Cheese Cake. I think the other places selling the same can fold. This rendition will put many businesses at risk. For those who tried, wasnâ€™t it crazy? Such fluff but packed with luxurious Goma taste, very feminine, the kind of craze that will drive Japanese nuts and therefore a good business model.
*******
So as we transit into Phase 2, I am sure we will miss all these wonderful gifts and experiments. But Caecilia, anytime you need someone to clean up the crumbs, let me know.... ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚

Mum and I love one pot meal. Easy to prepare and less stressful too because no need to coordinate the preparation time to ensure all dishes are served warm.

But my dad hor, he always hiamed (å«Œ or complain) that one pot meal is very å•è°ƒ or boring and he loves to see many dishes on the dining table #shouldbringhimtokoreanrestaurant #ilovebanchan

So hor, when mum is not very happy with him ğŸ¤­, she will purposely cook one pot meals, and vegetarian one somemore hahahah!

And that day, he was super sianz (bored and/or frustrated) because mum cooked vegetarian bee hoon for lunch and then lei cha for dinner LOL

Then then I remembered the packs of vegan-friendly @fupi.co snacks that I received the other day and fasterly went to Dad's rescue #åŠ æ–™ #gettingreadyforFathersDay #è¿˜æ˜¯å¥³å„¿è´´å¿ƒ#è‡ªå·±è®²çš„

I have seen these on the shelves of 7-eleven stores and have been curious about this as a snack. I mean we like eating beancurd skin soaked in soup where flavours of the soup is fully absorbed but to have it as a snack, lightly seasoned with top-notched popular hotpot soup flavours somemore, now that is really something new.

I tried them on their own as a snack and much prefer the tangy Hotpot Tomato over the spicy Sichuan Mala one.  Spicy ya but no numbing sensation or is it I numb to numbness ah ğŸ¤”

But hor, when I add them to the vegetarian bee hoon lunch and subsequently lei cha dinner, the mala seasoned one actually stood out more!  The spice elevated the flavours of the plain bee hoon (and lei cha) and added a rather interesting crispy texture.  Dad also copied me on how to zhng his lunch.. And dinner ğŸ˜‚

Fupi is also available on both Lazada and Shopee, do check out their website http://www.fupi.co/  for deets on how to order.

Thank you Eugene and @fupi.co for sending over the snacks ğŸ¥°

description:
Nonya cooking is akin to a wedding ritual. The preparation takes an arduous amount of time and work leading up to the actual assembly celebration. It was no surprise that this Nasi Lemak (ie. â€˜fatty riceâ€™) meal took me three days to prepare since the idea of getting everything done in a day didnâ€™t appeal to this mother who had other household chores to attend to. 
So day 1 began with the prepping of all the rempah for the Ayam Goreng Berempah (Malay Spiced Fried Chicken), Otah Otah and Samba Chili as well as to begin the marination for the chicken. I precooked my rempah paste for the otah and samba chili. The next day, it was frying the ikan bills (anchovies) and peanuts and steaming the Otah. Grilled Otah definitely tastes better but involves more time in the apportioning of the mixture into a number of banana leaf packets. I quick-sauteÌ a few table spoons of the fried ikan bills with the cooked sambal rempah and my Sambal Ikan Bills was done. 
Finally, it was down to the last wave of activities with the frying of the spiced chicken, and the cooking of the nasi leak rice and fried omelette. All the hard work culminated in a gratifying assembling ceremony that was almost therapeutic. Was it worth the effort? Certainly! But maybe once in a blue moonâ€¦

description:
I'm excited that we are entering Phase 2 tmr. Finally ... to be able to dine out again. If u haven't realised, most of us have been eating at the same dining table 3 meals a day for the past 2 months at least. It sure gets boring cleaning the freaking old table so many times a day. Has your dining table also attained much wear and tear recently? Lol.

So what do you want to eat out first? I miss everything, from restaurants to hawker centres, foodcourts, coffeeshops and even fast food outlets. I also miss eating zichar so much. Really miss the fun of sharing a variety of yummy Chinese dishes with family and friends in a relaxed dining environment that won't burn a big hole in your pockets ğŸ˜‹

Just look at these zichar dishes. Marmite pork ribs, signature tofu with enoki mushrooms and stir fried kailan with salted fish. They were the last zichar meal I had before the start of the Circuit Breaker. I never shared them here, so now I think it's apt to post and make you all crave zichar. Haha. Go go go, but please maintain some safe distancing and practise good hygiene when out and about yeh?

We celebrated Fatherâ€™s Day for my hubby tonight since weâ€™d be busy at my FILâ€™s this weekend. Hubs loves Jap food a lot and we had initially planned to go on a family trip to Japan in June to reward my lil princess for doing well in her studies last year, and have a feast! Now that weâ€™re grounded in SG (and home too!) means we get to try new places instead and I was sooo excited when I saw this Assorted Sashimi set on @alanloveshisboys IG. I wanted this to be a nice surprise for Hubs and boy was he delighted when he opened the box. This assorted sashimi set was not only melt-in-your-mouth delicious, it is super affordable. I checked out so many other places and really, for this variety of premium fish and abalone, bafun uni, murasaki uni, etc, youâ€™re getting a really good deal and I couldnâ€™t find anywhere else that offered such a value for money set. I really love all the details that went into this box and the flowers really added that extra touch. The customer service was top notch too and I like how they deliver it to your car when you drive down to pick it up :) When things settle down mid way through Phase 2, Iâ€™m gonna bring Hubs to the restaurant itself :) .

description:
#Youtiao (aka Chinese Fried #breadsticks) has to be the most versatile accompaniment on any Asian menu. It is a fried #bread variant like the #fried mantou. #Crispy on the outside, airy and fluffy on the inside, this natural duality makes it a great partner candidate for soups, #porridge to syrupy deserts in which Tau Suan comes to mind immediately. Another facet of its organic functionality is of course that it is also great as a stand-alone #breakfast or tea-time snack with soy milk/milk etc, which is really my favourite way of eating it. Anyway, once I have baked a batch, I tend to work my menu that week around it.

description:
Its time to show your Dad some love with delectable treats from @wsingapore at Sentosa Cove
.
The highlight of their menu is the Grandmaâ€™s Beef Ribs, 16 hour slow-cooked beef ribs with signature sauce from SKIRT which you can choose one top up from the likes of Something On The Side, Sweet Endings or Cocktails. The meltingly tender meat is highly recommended and is poised to leave you in awe
.
Also featured here is their Truffle Fries, Prosciutto Pizza and White Chocolate Oreo Cheesecake as well as two of their cocktails Seaside Green and Smack Jack  that one can enjoy from the comforts of your home. The Seaside Green is a concoction made of plantation rum, elderflower liqueur, mangosteen syrup, freshly squeezed grapefruit juice and freshly squeezed lemon juice while the Smack Jack is prepared using Jack Daniel no.7, Kahlua and mint .

description:
STIR FRIED BEEF w/ KAI LANâ¤ï¸
.
.
Loving this bright green Kai Lan (Chinese Broccoli) with marinated beef slices. So quick and easy! I  enjoyed so much my lunch for today. Yum! ğŸ˜‹ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
To Cook
1)Add 1 tsp each of corn starch, oil, and soy sauce to the beef in a bowl. Use your hands to massage these ingredients into the beef and set aside to marinate for 20 mins.
2)Heat a wok over high heat and add a tbsp of oil. When the oil starts to smoke, sear the beef for 30-60 secs, just until browned.
3)Remove from the wok and set aside.
4)Add 2 more tbsp of oil to the wok along with the ginger. Let the ginger caramelize for 15 secs.
5)Add the garlic and Chinese broccoli and stir fry for 1 min.
6)Add the beef, oyster sauce, soy sauce, salt, sugar, sesame oil, and hot beef stock then stir fry until mixed thoroughly.
7)Once the liquid comes to a boil, push the beef and vegetable away from the middle of the wok.
8)Stir in the corn starch slurry to thicken the sauce. Mix everything until the beef and vegetables are thoroughly coated.
8)Plate and serve over hot steamed rice.
.

A BIG THANKS to the fantastic team at @beurresg for sending over this delightful feast of fusion flavours! Check out the various pics and video! â©â©â©
.
This gastronomic feast consisted of their King Prawn Linguine, Mala Unagi Linguine, Black Pepper Wagyu Striploin Rice Bowl and Pulled Pork Samosa. Tasting these 4 creations 1 by 1 was tough as they were all delicious and it was hard to pick which to savour more! ğŸ”¥
.
King Prawn Linguine. This would be arguably the best of the lot. The prawns were huge and very fresh! The linguine was cooked al dente and just right (I cannot stand soggy pasta or noodles) and this was a huge plus point for me. Very nicely flavoured with umami seafood flavours, the whole dish just came together perfectly. It just didnâ€™t require anything else! ğŸ˜
.
Mala Unagi Linguine. This fusion twist was definitely memorably delicious and something for all Mala fans to try. Again, the pasta was cooked just perfect and flavoured perfectly with Mala peppers but just enough for the spice and flavour without numbing your tongue too much. The grilled unagi was done just right and it was surprising how well this complimented the Mala pasta. ğŸŒ¶
.
Black Pepper Wagyu Striploin Rice Bowl. The Wagyu beef stole the spotlight being tender and well marinated. Being a steak fan, this was definitely a treat but it was just overshadowed by the yummy pasta creations! ğŸ¥©
.
Pulled Pork Samosa. Last but not least, this looked underwhelming BUT tasted shockingly good! The meat was so tender and beautifully marinated. Excellent texture with perfect savoury bursts of flavour. ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»
.

description:
Special Menu by One Michelin Star @buonaterrasg ! Designed by and Compliments of Dr @corasephora (again). Quite a menu, rewrote my previous not-so-good experience at Buona Terra many years back.
*******
Everything clicked! Good spread of Mediterranean ingredients and techniques. Good compensation for travels and this meal showed that Take Outs can be beautiful too. I enjoyed the â€œBeef Agnolottiâ€ most, how not to like juicy bags of savoury Beef filling and shavings of Manjimup Truffle?? Wickedly delicious. Onto more meat, there were the signature Lamb Loins. Lovely crust on the top, cooked to pink, on a bed of eggplant caponata, delish! Seafood was not to be outdone, the second carbs of Squid Ink Risotto with Giant (capital G) Carabineros Prawn was an ultimate. I love anything squid ink and this was to the tee, lovely robust flavours of ink and butter, risotto cooked perfectly. There were more courses to rave about but I think Iâ€™ve made my point, â€œIt was a stunning take outâ€, enjoyed it tremendously..
*******

[Verdict: InTerrysting ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»] If youâ€™re at Ghim Moh, check out Tomâ€™s City Zoom Mee Pok Tar (01-11). This stall sells fish chor mee (é±¼è„é¢; as according to the Chinese wording of the signboard) as everything hereâ€™s served with fish. Fish ball, fish cake, fried fish dumpling and fried fish flakes served with mee pok thatâ€™s mixed well with chilli and vinegar. You get some lettuce for garnish. All these for $3.50 or $4.

I always have this as takeaway so I canâ€™t enjoy this dish in its fullest glory. Nevertheless, the strongest components of the dish were the springy fish balls, crunchy fried fish dumplings and the flavourful fish cakes since they put leek in the fish cake.

One thing I really like about the noodles here is that it doesnâ€™t become extremely soggy even when you have it as takeaway. It has a rather nice texture. But whatâ€™s great is that the noodles are well coated with the umami-filled chilli sauce and vinegar. And you can help yourself to the chilli padi. What a flavourful breakfast to begin with.

My only gripe is the lack of lard bits that I would very much prefer for extra texture and flavour.

The stall owner is a fine example of a hawkerpreneur. Donâ€™t go too late as they open early and sell out rather fast.

description:
This is no ordinary Chang. It is a keto-friendly bak chang, made with cauliflower rice. At $8 each for special keto food, I consider that a steal, especially when it is packed full of pork belly, mushrooms, chestnut, dried shrimp, scallops and a whole salted egg yolk. In terms of taste, I found it tasty, though a bit salty for my liking, but it feels so so so much more lighter on the stomach, cos itâ€™s good vegetable carbs - cauliflower, rather than the stodgier, traditional glutinous rice. So, for someone who tries to be low-carb till CB struck, these cauliflower zhang are awesome!

The creator is a mother-and-daughter pair. Mum is cabbie Eng Lan, who paused her 20-year cabbie career to shelter from Covid-19, and at the request of her daughter, Jeslyn, started making keto-friendly cauliflower rice bak chang. If you are keen to try, they are listed on FB group â€œPasar Unitedâ€. You can dm Jesslyn there. Island-wide delivery for $6 per location, and current delivery periods are June 20-22, and June 27-29.

Now that Phase 1 is coming to an end and weâ€™re headed into Phase 2 when we will get to eat out again, I thought Iâ€™d share what was the best take-out we had that everyone in the family enjoyed during CB and In Post-CB Phase 1... and that has to be Ginger Scallion Slices Pork Bento Set from @aoneclaypot...!
.
The generous portion, reasonable pricing (when your order directly from their website), packaging, but most importantly, the taste and flavour of its food. And I think my family would agree with me and will give them a rating of A-One for this simple and unassuming Bento. ğŸ˜‰
.
And talk about generous, our order always comes with a complimentary dish. While we donâ€™t expect it - that generous freebie never fails to lift our spirits up especially during this Covid session!
.
So, with Phase 2 just 2 days away, are we planning to head out to dine out? Tempting but probably not anytime soon. Stay home and stay safe!!

I got a real shock when mum said someone was waiting at the door for me - my sweet sister in Christ personally delivered these goodies - it was as if she saw what I wrote yesterday, knowing that I needed something sweet!  I think God heard my prayers and He sent an angel with so many sweets! Now my fridge is filled with goodies!  Thank you so much for the colourful love â¤ï¸ğŸ§¡ğŸ’›ğŸ’šğŸ’™ğŸ’œ.
.
Ok wait wait, that is not all... To my amazement, I found out that some of these were made by new found IG friend @tiaptiapwithsoph! What a surprise! Have been looking forward to the launch of her 50 shades of grey muah chee ğŸ–¤ and then this happened!

The muah chee was so soft and fragrant, I could really see the shallots in the dough.  I remember reading about eating it chilled so I tried it immediately!

I have to say I am totally digging the idea of DIY-ing your own muah chee and I had to control myself to not overdo the black sesame and grounded peanuts mix to muah chee dough ratio ğŸ¥°

Dad doesn't like to eat anything that is black (e.g. black sesame, black chicken, charred satay, charred char siew ğŸ¤”) so I am secretly very happy that I can help myself to the entire pack! #battlewithgreyhair! But but but Soph is so generous with the black sesame and grounded peanuts mix that I think I might have extras for mum to make black sesame milk buns ğŸ¤­

Ok, I am happy to report that my temper was super good today because #åƒç”œå“è„¾æ°”å¥½ and I might have had an overdose of sugar but #notcomplaining!

Saving the yam kueh for breakfast tomorrow ğŸ¥°

Thank you Lord for such a lovely sister with big heart and a wonderful and creative friend who can cook so well!

Ps. But I think God is not happy that someone is not sharing her address details with me and depriving me opportunity to show my love for my sister.

Pps. It is time someone update her address details with the company.

description:
Yeah I know, I overcooked the burger. Still tasty tho, and the extremely dense & meaty wagyu beef patties from @coldstoragesg are a carnivoreâ€™s paradise. â €
â €
You know I like em real thicc and juicy, and these here wagyu patties are most definitely both. Add a lil salt, pepper, garlic powder to season, then pan sear it. The trick is to treat it like steak: baste it with butter & some herbs for a first class ticket to Flavortown.

Melt a slice or two of cheese on it, put some bacon on top, then jam your meat between two toasty, brown & bouncy buns and youâ€™re almost there. Pour a pint of Stella Artois on the side and this is dynamite. Bomb dot com dynamite.â €

Gave my family and myself some hometown loving with a #beefhorfun #dinner. The dish works well with pork too. I usually soak the #beef / pork for a good 10-15 mins to leech the blood. This follows a good wringing as I squeeze out as much water as possible. I personally find this step necessary to minimize the iron taste in the meat. Anyway, I did the syrupy #blackbean version of the dish which we prefer over the dry stir-fry adaptation. A good beef #horfun is one with the characteristic â€˜wok heiâ€™ by flambeÌing the flat #noodle first. [Ingredients]
/Marinate Salmon/
-1 piece salmon @superseafoodsg
-1/2 lime
-1 tsp salt
-A pinch black pepper
-1 tsp white wine (optional)
.
/Broth & Rice/
-1 red onion (chopped)
-1 clove garlic (minced)
-8 pitted kalamata olives
-1.5 cup passata (tomato pureÌe)
-2 tbsp olive oil
-1.5 cups paella rice
-2-3 cups vegetables broth
-1 tsp salt
-A dash freshly ground black pepper -1/2 tsp paprika powder -1/2 tsp dried oregano
[Steps]
-Clean and cut salmon in cubes. Marinate with the marinate ingredients -Wash and drain rice. Set aside
-Heat olive oil in a pan on low-medium heat
-Add garlic and onion. Stir-fry until onion start to brown
-Stir in passata sauce. Stir-fry for 1 min and add in rice. Add paprika, oregano, and salt. Coat rice with sauce and spread the rice evenly in the pan
-From this point onward, do not stir the rice
-Add 2 cups of vegetable broth enough to cover the rice. Turn heat to low and let simmer for 20 mins. Check if the rice is almost cooked through. Add more broth and cook for a few mins longer if needed
-Spread olives and cubed salmon on top of the rice. Cover and let cook for 10 mins
-Uncover and sprinkle freshly grounded black pepper and serve hot out of the pan
.
.
.
